<%- include('partials/header.ejs') %>

<section class="stage-banner">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-label">Stage Three</p>
                <h1 class="section-title">Treatment Options & Government Funding</h1>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row align-items-center">
            <div class="col-md-8">
                <p class="section-intro">
                    Once your investigative cycle is complete and a diagnosis 
                    (or unexplained infertility) has been established, your specialist will discuss 
                    treatment options. In 2025, the Ontario government announced a 
                    <a href="https://news.ontario.ca/en/release/1006038/ontario-helping-more-families-access-fertility-supports" 
                       target="_blank" class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
                       title="Source: Ontario Newsroom, June 2025">$250 million investment</a> 
                    to expand fertility services across the province. Here is an overview 
                    of the most common treatment paths, what is covered, and how government funding 
                    can help.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4 text-center desktop-img">
                <img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/Ontario_buliding.jpg" 
                     alt="Ontario government fertility program announcement" 
                     style="max-width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-light">
	<div class="container">

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>IUI (Intrauterine Insemination)</h4>
			<p>
				Before jumping to IUI, your doctor may first suggest a simpler approach: 
				taking oral medication to stimulate ovulation, 
				then timing intercourse around your fertile window. If that does not work 
				after a few cycles, IUI is usually the next step.
			</p>
			<p>
				During an IUI procedure, sperm is collected, washed, and concentrated in 
				the lab to select the healthiest cells. The processed sample is then 
				injected directly into your uterus using a thin catheter, timed to 
				coincide with ovulation. The procedure itself takes only a few minutes 
				and is done at your fertility clinic. IUI may be done with or without 
				ovulation-stimulating medications, depending on your diagnosis.
			</p>

			<div class="highlight-box">
				<strong>IUI is fully funded under the Ontario Fertility Program (OFP).</strong>
				<ul class="highlight-box_list">
					<li>No limit on the number of IUI cycles you can receive.</li>
					<li>The insemination procedure, cycle monitoring, ultrasounds, and blood work are covered.</li>
					<li>Sperm washing (sperm preparation) is <b class="navy-text">not covered</b>. 
						Some clinics charge around <span class="orange-text">$775 per cycle</span>, 
						but prices vary by clinic.</li>
					<li>IUI can be done with or without fertility medications.</li>
					<li>If your doctor prescribes medications, those are also 
						<b class="navy-text">not covered</b> and cost approximately 
						<a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/get-fertility-treatments" target="_blank" 
						class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
						title="Source: Ontario Ministry of Health">
							<span class="orange-text">$1,000 per cycle</span></a>. 
						These costs may be partially covered by private insurance or claimed 
						through the Ontario Fertility Treatment Tax Credit.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>IVF — In Vitro Fertilization</h4>
			<p>Eggs are retrieved from the ovaries after a period of ovarian stimulation with injectable medications, fertilized in a lab, and the resulting embryo is transferred to the uterus.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>More involved process with daily injections over 10–14 days</li>
				<li>Requires frequent monitoring (blood work + ultrasound)</li>
				<li>Higher success rates than IUI, but also higher cost</li>
				<li>May involve additional procedures: ICSI, PGT (genetic testing), frozen embryo transfer</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="highlight-box">
			<strong>IVF is not the only option.</strong> In our focus group, every participant assumed IVF was the only fertility treatment available. In reality, your doctor may recommend IUI, medication-only cycles, or lifestyle changes first depending on your diagnosis. Treatment is not one-size-fits-all.
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>Ontario Fertility Program (OFP)</h4>
			<p>The Ontario government funds <strong>one IVF cycle per eligible patient per lifetime</strong> through the Ontario Fertility Program. This is something most people — including participants in our focus group — had no idea existed.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Covers the cost of one IVF cycle at participating clinics</li>
				<li>You must be an Ontario resident with a valid OHIP card</li>
				<li>There are eligibility criteria — your clinic will help determine if you qualify</li>
				<li>Waitlists apply and vary by clinic — some can be several months</li>
				<li>The funded cycle covers the procedure itself; medications and additional services (e.g., genetic testing, freezing) are typically not covered</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="mt-2">Ask your clinic about OFP eligibility early. Knowing the waitlist length at different clinics may also factor into your clinic choice back in Stage 1.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="cost-box">
			<strong>Cost note:</strong> Even with OFP funding, expect out-of-pocket costs for medications (which can range from hundreds to thousands of dollars), monitoring fees, and optional add-ons like genetic testing. Some private insurance plans cover a portion of fertility medications — check with your employer's benefits plan.
		</div>

		<%- include('partials/quiz-stage3') %>
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-between mt-5">
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/stage2" class="btn btn-outline-sage">← Stage 2: Investigative Cycle</a>
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/" class="btn btn-sage">Back to Home</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

</main>
